1. Set-Based Similarity

These compare overlap between words, tokens, or character groups.

Jaccard Similarity

You mentioned “Jaccard.” It measures overlap between two sets.

J(A,B)=
∣A∪B∣
∣A∩B∣
	​


J(A,B)=
∣A∪B∣
∣A∩B∣
	​


Example

Text A:

"machine learning is fun"

Text B:

"learning machine is powerful"

Token sets:

A = {machine, learning, is, fun}
B = {learning, machine, is, powerful}

Intersection = 3
Union = 5

Similarity = 3/5 = 0.6

Good for
Duplicate detection
Search indexing
Tag matching
Near-identical documents
Weakness

Doesn’t understand meaning.

“car” and “automobile” look unrelated.

Dice Coefficient

Similar to Jaccard but weighted differently.

Dice(A,B)=
∣A∣+∣B∣
2∣A∩B∣
	​


Dice(A,B)=
∣A∣+∣B∣
2∣A∩B∣
	​


Often used in NLP and fuzzy matching.

2. Edit Distance Techniques

These measure how many changes are needed to transform one text into another.

Levenshtein Distance

Counts insertions, deletions, substitutions.

Example

"kitten" → "sitting"

Operations:

kitten → sitten
sitten → sittin
sittin → sitting

Distance = 3

Good for
Spell checking
OCR correction
Username matching
Fuzzy search
Damerau-Levenshtein

Adds transposition support.

Example:

"hte" → "the"

Very useful for typo detection.

Hamming Distance

Counts differing characters at same positions.

Only works for equal-length strings.

Example:

1011101
1001001

Distance = 2

3. Vector Space / Statistical Methods

These convert text into numerical vectors.

Cosine Similarity

One of the most common NLP similarity methods.

Measures angle between vectors.

cos(θ)=
∣∣A∣∣ ∣∣B∣∣
A⋅B
	​


cos(θ)=
∣∣A∣∣ ∣∣B∣∣
A⋅B
	​


Usually used with
TF-IDF vectors
Bag-of-words
Embeddings
Good for
Document similarity
Search engines
Recommendation systems
TF-IDF

Weights words by importance.

Rare words matter more than common words.

Example:

“the” gets low weight
“transformer” gets high weight

Often combined with cosine similarity.

4. Semantic Similarity (Meaning-Based)

These try to understand meaning rather than exact wording.

Word Embeddings

Words become vectors in high-dimensional space.

Examples:

Word2Vec
GloVe
FastText

Interesting property:

vector("king")−vector("man")+vector("woman")≈vector("queen")
Good for
Semantic search
Recommendation
Clustering
Sentence Embeddings

Modern NLP usually compares sentence embeddings.

Models:

Sentence-BERT
Universal Sentence Encoder
OpenAI embeddings

Example:

“I love programming”
“Coding is enjoyable”

These become nearby vectors even with different words.

Common approach
Convert text → embeddings
Compute cosine similarity
